{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_circle_ver01/data/sn85053043/0051717841A/1937121001/0599.xml":{"full_text":"The Glacier Count y_Chief\nEntered as Bad data flatter\nJuly 15, 1931 at the pcatoftlea at\nBrowning, Mont., under the net of\nMarch 3, 1879.\nMgacriptioo 82.00 year In advMco\nJACK DUNCAN\nEditor and Publisher\nA weekly newspaper published every\nFriday at Browning, Glacier County,\nThe Low Down\nFrom Hickory Grove\nAbout every other day, when you\npick up a paper, you will fee where\nthey are ehootiu'another d sen or\none-half dozen, over there in Rus\nsia. And pretty soon they are gonna\nhave to do quite a little lot-kin\u2019\naround, to Hud people to ehoot.\nLike inearlydaye in the U. S they\nhad plenty of buff.ilo and they\nthought they would never run out\nof \u2019em, and they shot \u2019em just for a\nbuffalo robe.\nAnd some day it will maybe be\nthe same in Russia. And it is kinda\nfunhy that you will find people\nhere in the U S. A., on soap boxes\nand other places, here and here\nand you will find \u2019em fav*r< mak\ning over our Govt., air try out\nsome foreign idea, or some new ism\nor asm that has not bem used, but\nsounds great.\nBut the ducks talkin' up these\nbig ideas, they would not be so hot\nfor \u2019em, except they figure they\nmaybe can be the top-sergeant, with\na nice new job, and a new fur-lined\nover-coat \u2014and not the guy sUndiu\u2019\nup against the wall.\nYours, with the low-down,\nJO SERRA\nGOOD ADVICE TO CONGRESS\nA dozen leading economists re\ncently presented to the special ses\nsion of Congress a four-point formu\nla for ending the slump in business\nactivity.\nThe gist of it was, according to\nan Associated Press report, \u201cDo\nsomething to encourage business.\u2019\u2019\nThe four points included; Abolish\nments of the tax on undistributed\nprofits; revision or abolishment of\nthe tax on capital gains; ending of\ngovernment competition with busi\nness; the bolstering of confidence\nby definitely indicating an intention\nto balance the budget as soon as\npossible and practical.\nIn addition, members of the\ngroup advocated cooperation be\ntween labor and business on wages,\nprices and employment, and a pro\nperly conducted housing drive. All\nagreed with the statement of Mr.\nFriday when he said: \"Thore is\nneed of some definite, dramatie ac\ntion to show that government pro\nmiaea of helping business are more\nthan just a lot of talk.\u2019\u2019\nCongress has been holding open\nseason on business. Industry has\nbeen sniped at from all quarters. It\nhas been reviled, denounced and\nsaddled with an unprecedented\nweight of punitive laws. The inevi\ntable results are seen today: Worried\ninvestors, discouraged manage\nments, retrenchment of capital\u2014\nall culminating in a major business\nrecession. Continuance of this trend\nmust inevitably turn the recession\ninto a depression.\nThe four actions the econ mists\nlist would go a long wav toward\nbringing back lost confidence. They\nwould instantly encourage the\nspending ol money, tba building of\nplants, the expansion of inventories,\nand the employment of men and\nwomen. Congress never got better\nadvice.\nTEN COMMANMENTS\nAs given by Bishop George Craig\nStewart, of the Episcopal ebureb,\nin an address before the Chamber\nof Commerce. Evanston, Illinois,\nSafety Council and members of the\nEvanston police department, at the\nawarding of the National Safety\nCouncil's plaque to the city of Evau-\nEton as America\u2019s safest city.\n1 Thou shall keep \u201cSafety First\u2019\u2019\never before thee.\n2 Tbou shall not make of thyself\na dangerous nuisance, nor the like\nnene of anyone that grabbeth the\nroad ahead and cutteth in and ont\nof line. Thou shall btware of such\nand elow up for him, for ho is a\nwild and zealous fellow, visiting the\niniquity of his follies upon the chil\ndren in school zones from genera\ntion to generation and showing off\nunto thousands of bis bettors who\nare trying to keep the command\n\u25a0onto.\n8 Thou abalt not take the laws of\nthe stale in vain for the cop and the\njndfls will not hold him guiltleeo\nahai toketh the laws in vain.\n4 Esaneaibsr thy brakes and tires\nand take corvee slowly.\n5 Kanae the Bad Lights and Iba\nGreen Llgbla, that tby daya may be\nlong in the lend which Lord thy\nGod giveth thee.\n8. Thou shalt not kill,\n7 Thou shalt not stop abruptly.\n8 Thou shaft not steal \u2014past a\nstreetcar, loading and unloading.\n9 Though shall not flash bright\nlights against thy heighbor.\n10 Thou shalt not shove-it,\nthy neighbors car, nor his bumper,\nnor his locks, nor his glass, nor nor\nthing that is thy neighbors.\nSpecial Session of Congress\nHas Reverse Effect on Condition\nWhen President Roosevelt called t\nthe special session of Congress, the I\naountry was virtually in a boom I\nstage, as compared with today\u2019s]\nconditions. Stocks were at high'\nlevels. Reemployment was going\nahead on a comfort ible scale.\nThough unfavorable signs existed,\nthey were few and apparently insig\nnificant, and almost everything!\npointed to a highly prosperous win- 1\nter season.\nNow, in two months, the picture\nhas changed completely. Stocks,\nin spite of occasional flurries, are!\nholding stubbornly at levels close;\nto October lows. With few excep\nlions, industrial production contin-;\nues to sag. Unemployment is in\ncreasing alarmtngiy. And it is;\nvery likely that this winter\u2019s relief\nproblem will be ns grave as in any i\nyear since 1929.\nOne result of this is a complete\nchange in the attitude of Congress\n\u2014and, to a leaser degree, a change!\nin tbe attituoe of the administra-1\ntion. The special session was pri- i\nmarily called for three purposes-\u2014|\nthe wage and hourt law, the farm]\nrelief proposal, and the bill to cre\nate seven new regional electric\nauthorities similar in nature to the I\nTVA. It was assumed that these\nmatters would absorb the undivid-1\ned attention of the session, and that\nnothing else of moment would be\nbrought up on the floor or in com\nmittee.\nWhat has happened? The wage\nand hours law is in a state of chaos,\nwith warring factions seeking to\nchange it one way or another, and\nwith a strong congressional bloc op\nposed to the passage of any law of\nits type. The chances are against\nit going through in the special ses\nsion.\nThe farm bill is in a similar pre\ndicament \u2014it seems uiim-al impos\nsible that a law satisfactory to the\nvarious opposed factious in House\nand Senate can be prepared for\nmonths.\nI The seven regional authorities\nbill is, accordii g to last reports,\ncompletely moribund.\nCongress is almost wholly oc\ncupied with the business reces\nsion, and with proposals designed\nto prevent it from becoming an\nother major, long lasting depres\neion. Tax reform seems nearer\nto achievement than at any time\nin the last four years. I here is\ndefinite sentiment in favor of a\nmore conciliatory general policy\ntoward industry. There is a\ngrowing feeling that we have\ngone too far with regulation, es\npecially as it affects the security\nmarkets and exchanges. There\nis a movement on foot to encour\nage business to spend on a big\nacale\u2014of which the most signi\nficant development is the Presi\ndent\u2019s announced policv of a more\nfriendly attitude toward the elec-,\ntrie utilities, and his recent talks\nwith utility executives.\nThe principal question now is.\nCan Congress act fast enough\nand drastically enough to stop\nthe decline? Some recent events\nhave been encouraging, but they\nby no means assure a change in\ntbe downward trend. Whatever\nhappens, it seems impossible for\nany important change to take\nplace before late January\u2014a fact\nwhich augurs badly for the\nChristmas season.\nEXPECTANCY\nThere are many who wait for their\nships to come in,\nFor their ships to come in from\nBlackfeet Reservation\nPost 127\nK; f l, \"TC'\".''\nIt -7 1 s t\nA c v\nMeets First Tuesday ed eaeh\nMonth. VMttog Tioginealreo\nMM 